---
import Page from '@/layouts/Page.astro'
import { SITE } from '@/lib/site'

export const prerender = true

const lastUpdated = '9 May 2026'
---

<Page
  title="Privacy"
  description="What trominal.app and the public demo backend collect — and don't."
  active="privacy"
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>Privacy</span>
      <h1>What we collect — and what we don't.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Plain English. No tracking pixels, no behavioral profiling, no third-party ad networks.
        Last updated {lastUpdated}.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section flush">
    <div class="wrap">
      <article class="prose" style="max-width:760px">
        <p>
          This page covers two things: <strong>{SITE.domain}</strong> (the marketing site
          you're reading) and <strong>{new URL(SITE.demo.backendUrl).host}</strong> (the public
          demo backend). It does <em>not</em> cover instances of Trominal that you self-host —
          those are governed by whoever runs them.
        </p>

        <h2>The marketing site (this site)</h2>

        <h3>What we collect automatically</h3>
        <p>
          We use <strong>Cloudflare Real User Measurements (RUM)</strong>, a privacy-friendly
          analytics service that runs without cookies and without persistent identifiers. It
          records:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Page paths visited and approximate request volume</li>
          <li>Referrer (where the request came from)</li>
          <li>Browser type and operating system at a coarse granularity</li>
          <li>Country (derived from the request IP at edge level — IP itself is not stored)</li>
          <li>
            Core Web Vitals — page load timing, layout shift, and interactivity metrics — to
            help us spot performance regressions
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          That data is aggregated by Cloudflare. We use it to understand which pages are
          useful, which feel slow, and which aren't loading. There is no per-user profile and
          nothing follows you across sessions.
        </p>

        <h3>What we don't collect</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>No cookies of our own</li>
          <li>No tracking pixels, no Google Analytics, no Meta pixel, no LinkedIn pixel</li>
          <li>No behavioral profiles, no fingerprinting</li>
          <li>No A/B testing platforms</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Embedded GitHub data</h3>
        <p>
          Star counts, contributor counts, and release info are fetched from the public GitHub
          API by our Cloudflare Worker. The Worker caches results and serves them from
          <code>/api/stats.json</code>. Your browser only ever talks to
          <code>{SITE.domain}</code>; it does not contact GitHub directly.
        </p>

        <h3>Contact email</h3>
        <p>
          When you email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a>, your
          message lands in a regular inbox. We keep correspondence as long as needed to answer
          you. We do not subscribe you to anything. We do not share email content with third
          parties.
        </p>

        <h2>The demo backend</h2>

        <h3>What the demo stores</h3>
        <p>
          When you register on <code>{SITE.demo.backendUrl}</code> from a Trominal client, the
          server stores:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Email address (used for login and password reset). You can use a throwaway address.
          </li>
          <li>An Argon2id-hashed password used to authenticate API sessions</li>
          <li>Your KDF salt, your public key, and ciphertext blobs the client uploads</li>
          <li>Audit log entries with action type, IP, and user-agent (90-day retention)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The server <strong>cannot decrypt</strong> the ciphertext blobs. Your master password
          never leaves your device — see <a href="/security">the threat model</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Database resets</h3>
        <p>
          The demo's database is wiped periodically and without notice. Treat the demo as
          ephemeral. To keep what you build, run your own server (see
          <a href="/install">install</a>).
        </p>

        <h3>Acceptable use</h3>
        <p>
          The demo runs on shared infrastructure. Don't use it for production work, large
          imports, automated load testing, or anything that violates
          <a href="/terms">the terms</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Logs</h3>
        <p>
          The Caddy reverse proxy in front of the demo writes short-lived access logs (path,
          status, latency, IP) for diagnostic purposes. Logs are rotated daily. The Trominal
          application itself never writes secrets, plaintext keys, or vault contents to logs.
        </p>

        <h2>Self-hosted instances</h2>
        <p>
          When you self-host Trominal, this privacy policy does not apply to your instance —
          you, the operator, are the data controller. Trominal does not phone home, does not
          send telemetry, and does not contact any Trominal-operated server unless you
          explicitly point it there.
        </p>

        <h2>Your rights</h2>
        <p>
          For the demo backend: email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a>
          to request deletion of your account and any associated ciphertexts. We will action
          requests within 30 days, sooner where possible.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the marketing site: there is no per-visitor data tied to you to delete, since
          analytics are aggregate-only.
        </p>

        <h2>Changes to this policy</h2>
        <p>
          When this page changes, the date at the top updates and the diff lands in the public
          repo at <a
            href={`${SITE.github.url}/commits/main/website/src/pages/privacy.astro`}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener">website/src/pages/privacy.astro</a>. No silent edits.
        </p>

        <h2>Questions</h2>
        <p>
          Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a> — the same
          person reading the privacy mail also reviews the code.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Page>
